No, apparently not. The creature merely hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry when she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill them?" shouted Nyssi.
"TARGET THEIR HEADS!"
"THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but quickly became panicky when it was hit by a beam of fire from behind. It hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. It became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, knocking it off course.
Growling and snarling, it flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly turned dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
As soon as he could see nothing anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before finally plunging onto a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and charged straight at him, dragging the black cloud with her.
"Kayel!" shouted Tenuk as he slid out of the cloud and began circling to look for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now, Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Nyssi painfully got to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. Unfortunately, this was not the case for Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And within that shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A fearsome, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground, knocking her down. However, she noticed that the tail was just flailing wildly and not intentionally trying to hit her. The beast, or rather, the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot rang out through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel was standing on the beast, heavily panting while holding his rifle.
"That was... probably the craziest shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", gasped Cable, gasping for breath. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But as he continued speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them because most people found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could also use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he obviously seemed quite surprised as well.
"Are you okay?" broke out of Nyssi.
"Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be back to normal in a moment." Kayel examined his work as Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and resumed his usual spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns extended from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to skid to a halt right in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died right there on the spot.
"Ups...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. "Uh, that wasn't intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the action," Tenuk scolded. "Where were you?"
"I've been left alone by all of you. I came as soon as I could...", sighed Retvik. "May I ask what those terrible creatures are?"
Fortunately, Thassalin answered Retvik's question, having recovered somewhat. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED ONES! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE HERE, AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean that terrible god-beast thing that we... helped kill?" stuttered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MAYBE THERE IS EVEN MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT IN HIS HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, RIGHT?" Thassalin limped over to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO TALENTED AT KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSes."
"Uh... thanks... I think...," shrugged Kayel. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took some pictures of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the ornate god of death dagger, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns. She then moved on to the second one. But just as Nyssi finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash within seconds. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time...", sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
